":963,"1316":663,"1317":441,"1318":1186,"1319":664,"1320":746,"1321":987,"1322":934,"1323":426,"1324":625,"1325":999,"1326":629,"1327":387,"1328":327,"1329":328,"1330":260,"1331":568,"1332":1247,"1333":1238,"1334":747,"1335":1194,"1336":468,"1337":763,"1338":339,"1339":95,"1340":172,"1341":748,"1342":417,"1343":370,"1344":1344,"1345":128,"1346":142,"1347":956,"1348":1100,"1349":1137,"1350":261,"1351":851,"1352":477,"1353":1277,"1354":876,"1355":200,"1356":803,"1357":206,"1358":1085,"1359":805,"1360":863,"1361":55,"1362":898,"1363":1054,"1364":902,"1365":903,"1366":1032,"1367":926,"1368":457,"1369":574,"1370":927,"1371":969,"1372":450,"1373":1187,"1374":970,"1375":1018,"1376":556,"1377":1188,"1378":1019,"1379":1021,"1380":1262,"1381":1189,"1382":1022,"1383":894,"1384":390,"1385":1190,"1386":967,"1387":455,"1388":905,"1389":1191,"1390":1093},"orderedDocs":[[1011,"\"Unable to connect to LND\""],[876,"(Alternatively, create the wallet first and then run\n`lncli restorechanbackup --multi_file /tmp/channel.backup`.\nSame end result.)"],[385,"(Optional) Connect over Tor"],[349,"(Optional) Gate the UI with a password. Any username works; only\nthe password is checked. Use &#x2A;*password \\[D]** from\nPreparations:"],[386,"(Optional) Tor proxy for external services"],[236,"**\"Cannot bind to 0.0.0.0:8333\"**, port 8333 is already in\nuse, likely by a leftover process. Kill it and retry."],[234,"**\"Cannot obtain a lock on data directory\"**, another\n`bitcoind` is already running, or a previous one didn't shut\ndown cleanly. Check with `pgrep bitcoind`."],[235,"**\"Error opening block database\"**, disk is full, disk is\nfailing, or the indexes are corrupt. If the filesystem is\nhealthy, reindex with `-reindex`."],[243,"**`lnd.conf`**, the `[Bitcoin]` and `[Bitcoind]` sections must\npoint at the right ZMQ ports and RPC credentials."],[624,"**2 TB USB 3 SSD** in an external enclosure"],[731,"**Admin privileges with `sudo`**, the `admin` user can't change\nsystem files directly, which is deliberate. Prefix any such\ncommand with `sudo` (\"superuser do\"), and the Pi asks for your\npassword before running it. Service users like `bitcoin` (coming\nlater) have no `sudo` at all, that's intentional too."],[948,"**Auto-unlock** from a file on disk. Trades at-rest encryption\nfor uptime. On a single-user home node behind a firewall this is\nthe right default; an attacker who can read files as `lnd` has\nalready lost you the game."],[391,"**BitBoxApp**, the natural choice\nif you hold a BitBox02 hardware wallet."],[511,"**Bitcoin Core 30.2** running as a systemd\nservice, syncing the full blockchain, routing outbound through Tor."],[513,"**BTC RPC Explorer** giving you a private web UI for blocks,\ntransactions, mempool, and fee estimates."],[902,"**Caddy** is running as the reverse proxy for your LAN-only\nservices, installed earlier in the Bitcoin section."],[245,"**Chain sync**, LND won't start routing until `bitcoind` is\nfully synced. A stuck IBD will look like a stuck LND."],[730,"**Command history**, press the up and down arrow keys to cycle\nthrough previous commands. No need to retype anything."],[578,"**Configure wifi**, only if you plan to connect over Wi-Fi.\nEnter the SSID and password, and set the two-letter country code\n(e.g. `US`, `DE`, `CH`). Leave this blank if you'll use Ethernet,\nwhich, if you're sitting near the router, is what you want."],[733,"**Copy and paste**, in most terminals, highlight with the mouse\nto copy and press `Ctrl`-`Shift`-`V` to paste. On macOS Terminal,\nuse `Cmd`-`C` / `Cmd`-`V`. In Windows Terminal, right-click to\npaste at the cursor."],[424,"**Create a wallet** → **New Wallet** → choose a name. For real\nfunds, pick **Connect Hardware Wallet** and let Sparrow import the\npublic keys (xpubs) from your device. The wallet is now watch-only:\nit can see, but not spend."],[973,"**Do not** photograph the screen, do not type the words into any\ntext file, do not email them to yourself, do not put them in a\npassword manager unless it's one you trust with your life."],[732,"**Editing files with nano**, this guide uses the `nano` editor.\nTo save: press `Ctrl`-`O`, confirm the filename, press Enter.\nTo exit: press `Ctrl`-`X`. That's it. (If you already love `vim`\nor `emacs`, use those; nano is just the friendliest default.)"],[512,"**Electrs 0.11.1** indexing the chain for your desktop\nwallet, no more leaking addresses to public Electrum servers."],[392,"**Electrum desktop**, the original.\nPowerful, a little austere, and still the yardstick for Electrum\nserver compatibility."],[581,"**Enable SSH*&#x2A;, check the box and select &#x2A;*\"Use password\nauthentication\"**. This lets you reach the Pi over the network\nin the next section."],[417,"**Guest WiFi strikes again.** \"Guest\" or \"isolated\" WiFi networks\non most home routers block client-to-client traffic, which is\nexactly what you need. Switch to the main WiFi."],[1099,"**Home**, headline numbers. On-chain balance, channel balance,\npayments, invoices, and node ranking at a glance."],[422,"**Hostname resolution.** If `raspibolt.local` doesn't resolve,\nuse the Pi's IP address. Some Windows setups never enable mDNS by\ndefault."],[701,"**iOS / Android:** Tailscale in the App Store or Play Store."],[51,"**LAN** over your home network. Fastest, works only when you're\non the same Wi-Fi. Same hardened SSH config as everywhere else."],[394,"**Ledger Live** or **Trezor Suite**, OK if you're already in\nthose ecosystems; both can point at your Bitcoin Core RPC. Less\nflexible than Sparrow."],[1100,"**Lightning → Channels**, open channels, pending channels, and\nthe button to open a new one. Channel policy (base fee, fee\nrate, time lock) lives in the per-channel view."],[1101,"**Lightning → Payments**, pay an invoice by pasting it, or\ngenerate one to receive. The payments table shows every Lightning\npayment the node has sent."],[699,"**Linux:** the same apt commands above, swapping `trixie` for your distribution's codename. Or the one-liner `curl -fsSL https://tailscale.com/install.sh | sh`."],[719,"**Linux**: use whichever terminal your distribution ships."],[107,"**LND data** (`/data/lnd` or `/mnt/ext/lnd`, depending on version)"],[893,"**LND** running as a systemd service, connected to bitcoind over\nRPC + ZMQ, and routing its own peer traffic through Tor."],[698,"**macOS:** `brew install tailscale && sudo tailscale up`, or the Mac App Store app."],[718,"**macOS**: open **Terminal** from `Applications → Utilities`."],[303,"**Main takeaway:** `bitcoind` is running under its own user, syncing\nthe chain through Tor, and exposing the RPC and ZMQ surfaces the\nnext services in this guide will plug into."],[784,"**Main takeaway:** any IP that fumbles five logins gets a\nten-minute timeout, automatically, in the background, forever."],[54,"**Main takeaway:** Bitcoin Core and LND use Tor to hide **your**\nidentity from the peer network. Tailscale lets **you** reach the Pi\nfrom anywhere without exposing it to the peer network. Different\nprivacy problems, different tools."],[11,"**Main takeaway:** Bitcoin Core is the only service that actually\nvalidates the chain. Everything else is a consumer of that one\nanswer."],[497,"**Main takeaway:** Electrs is indexing on `:50001`, stunnel wraps it\nin TLS on `:50002`, and the firewall lets LAN wallets in. The next\npage points Sparrow at it."],[49,"**Main takeaway:** if the SD card fails, your funds are safe on the\nSSD. If the SSD fails and you have the seed phrase and the latest\n`channel.backup`, you can recover funds from every channel. The\nChannel backup page sets that up."],[985,"**Main takeaway:** LND is up, the wallet is unlocked, the 24-word\nseed is on paper, and `lncli` works from `admin`. You have a\nworking Lightning node."],[776,"**Main takeaway:** nothing reaches the Pi from the network except\nrate-limited SSH, every other port stays shut by default."],[767,"**Main takeaway:** only your private key can reach the Pi over\nSSH now, passwords are off the table."],[883,"**Main takeaway:** the seed is half of recovery, the SCB is the\nother half, and the SCB is only useful if it lives somewhere the\nPi's SSD can't take with it. Set up the sync, test it, and keep\nan eye on the freshness."],[688,"**Main takeaway:** Tor is running and ready; the apps that matter\nwill plug into it later in the guide."],[705,"**Main takeaway:** Tor keeps Bitcoin and Lightning peer traffic\nprivate. Tailscale keeps your own remote access private and\nconvenient. Different jobs, different tools, you want both."],[429,"**Main takeaway:** with Sparrow talking to your node and a hardware\nwallet plugged in, you have a setup that sits cleanly at the top of\nthe self-custody tree, private, verified, spendable, and yours."],[367,"**Main takeaway:** you can now browse blocks, transactions, and\nfee estimates at `https://raspibolt.local:4000` without telling\nanyone else what you're looking at."],[1050,"**Main takeaway:** you have full, private control of your\nLightning node from your phone, payments, channel management,\ninvoicing, with zero third-party infrastructure between you and\nyour own Pi."],[1361,"**Main takeaway:** you now have a private Bitcoin block explorer and\nmempool visualizer. The node's own Electrs index answers every query."],[1105,"**Main takeaway:** you now have a proper dashboard on your LAN.\nEverything `lncli` does, RTL does with a mouse, plus graphs."],[947,"**Manual unlock** every time the Pi reboots. Most secure at rest:\nthe password lives only in your head, but a power blip at 3 a.m.\nleaves LND offline until you're awake to type a password."],[843,"**Never use the SCB on a node that is still running the same\nchannels elsewhere.** Restoring triggers force-closes; doing\nthat against a node that thinks the channels are fine gets your\nbalances punished to the peer. Treat the SCB like a one-shot\nrecovery tool."],[1104,"**Node Settings → Services → Watchtowers**, the towers you\nconfigured with `lncli wtclient add` show up here too."],[1103,"**On-chain**, deposits, sends, UTXOs, and the sweep tool."],[208,"**Open issues on GitHub.**\nSomeone probably hit it first. If you find the issue, the fix\nmight already be in the comments."],[412,"**Port:** `50002`."],[442,"**Proxy URL:** `127.0.0.1`. &#x2A;*Port:** `9050` (daemon) or `9150`\n(Tor Browser)."],[427,"**PSBT:** if the signing device lives air-gapped (a Coldcard with\nan SD card, for example), export a Partially Signed Bitcoin\nTransaction, sign on the cold device, and import the signed PSBT\nback. Same result; no USB."],[10,"**Reading the arrows.** A one-way arrow is the direction a request\nflows: the caller talks, the callee answers. The protocol label is\nthe channel. **RPC** is JSON-over-HTTP to Bitcoin Core. **gRPC** is\nLND's binary protocol. **ZMQ** is Bitcoin Core pushing new-block and\nnew-transaction events to LND without polling. **SOCKS** is Tor's\nway of letting an application route its outbound traffic through the\nonion network. **TLS** is Electrum over stunnel, HTTPS is everything\ngoing through Caddy, and SSH is how you reach the Pi (directly on\nthe LAN, or through Tailscale from anywhere else)."],[425,"**Receive:** go to the **Receive** tab, give the next address a\nlabel, and share it. Label everything you can. Future-you will\nthank present-you every time you look at a transaction history."],[841,"**Recovery depends on your peers being online and honest.** An\noffline peer means locked funds until they come back. A\nmalicious peer could, in principle, refuse."],[895,"**Ride The Lightning (RTL)** on `https://rtl.raspibolt.local`,\nreachable from your LAN so you can manage channels in a browser."],[1102,"**Routing**, earnings from forwarded payments, plus a per-peer\nbreakdown. This is where you'll see whether your channel policy\nis attracting any volume."],[244,"**RPC credentials**, if you rotated `bitcoind`'s cookie or\nRPC password without updating `lnd.conf`, LND will fail to\nconnect."],[109,"**Seed phrase and passwords** (you wrote those down, right?)"],[426,"**Send:** pick the UTXOs you want to spend from the **UTXOs** tab\n(this is coin control, an underrated privacy tool), draft the\ntransaction, and let your hardware wallet sign it. Sparrow shows\nthe exact bytes the device will sign, every fee, and every\nchange output. Nothing is hidden."],[576,"**Set hostname**, choose a name for your node, for example\n`raspibolt`. The Pi then answers to `raspibolt.local` from any\ndevice on the same network that speaks mDNS (most do)."],[579,"**Set locale settings**, pick your timezone and keyboard layout."],[577,"**Set username and password**, turn this on, enter the username\n`admin`, and use your &#x2A;*password \\[A]**. Every command in this\nguide assumes the user is called `admin`."],[514,"**Sparrow Wallet** on your laptop, talking to your own Electrum\nserver over TLS, ready to drive a hardware wallet."],[393,"**Specter Desktop**,\nfocused on multisig and air-gapped workflows. Connects directly\nto Bitcoin Core rather than Electrs."],[418,"**Stale certificate.** If you used Sparrow before connecting to\na *different* Electrum server at the same hostname, delete the\ncached certs and try again:"],[108,"**Static channel backup** (`channel.backup`)"],[729,"**Tab completion**, press `Tab` to auto-complete commands,\nfilenames, and paths. Press it twice to see all matches. Once you\nstart using it you'll wonder how you ever lived without it."],[52,"**Tailscale mesh** from any of your own devices, anywhere in the\nworld. No ports open on your router, no dynamic DNS, WireGuard\nend-to-end."],[541,"**Tailscale** installed so you can SSH into the Pi from anywhere,\nno router ports opened, no dynamic DNS."],[209,"**The FAQ.** Answers to the questions that aren't\nreally \"bugs\", upgrading, restoring backups, Linux basics."],[53,"**Tor hidden service** for mobile Lightning (Zeus). Your phone\nreaches LND's REST interface over an `.onion` address nobody else\nknows."],[671,"**Tor** (The Onion Router) is a free, open-source anonymity network\nmaintained by the Tor Project. Traffic\nis encrypted in layers and bounced through a handful of volunteer\nrelays, so no single hop sees both where it came from and where it's\ngoing. Bitcoin Core and LND will plug into it later in the guide."],[901,"**Tor** is installed and its SOCKS proxy is live on\n`127.0.0.1:9050` (see Privacy)."],[411,"**URL:** `raspibolt.local` (or your Pi's IP, e.g. `192.168.0.20`)."],[432,"**URL:** your `.onion` address. &#x2A;*Port:** `50002`. &#x2A;*SSL:** on."],[700,"**Windows:** installer from tailscale.com/download."],[720,"**Windows**: open **Windows Terminal** or **PowerShell** from the\nStart menu."],[972,"**Write the words down on paper.** Twice. Keep the two copies in\ntwo different physical locations."],[207,"**Your own notes.** The most common cause of a broken node is a\nstep that was skipped or done in a different order."],[842,"**Your SCB must be current.** If the peer closes at a state\nnewer than the one in your SCB, LND sees a state it doesn't\nrecognise and refuses to claim. You'll still get a force-close\nfrom the peer, just the slow path, not the SCB-accelerated one."],[896,"**Zeus** on your phone, connected to the Pi over a private Tor\nonion, full node control from wherever you are."],[1339,"\\~5 GB free on the SSD: build artefacts under `/home/mempool/` take 4-5 GB; the MariaDB database starts small but\ngrows to \\~5 GB with full historical address indexing enabled"],[41,"\\~70 GB"],[38,"\\~700 GB, +7 GB/month"],[641,"`[ A ]`"],[643,"`[ B ]`"],[645,"`[ C ]`"],[647,"`[ D ]`"],[649,"`[ E ]`"],[36,"`/data/bitcoin`"],[39,"`/data/electrs`"],[45,"`/data/lnd/data/chain/bitcoin/mainnet/channel.backup`"],[42,"`/data/lnd`"],[900,"`bitcoind` exposes the RPC port on `127.0.0.1:8332` and the ZMQ\nstreams on ports `28332` and `28333`, exactly as configured in\nBitcoin client."],[266,"`bitcoind` runs as its own system user. No shell password, no\nsudo, if something ever does manage to break out of the daemon, it\nlands in a sandbox, not on your `admin` account."],[233,"`bitcoind` will log its entire startup sequence: config file\nparsing, data directory checks, cache sizing, block index load,\nnetwork bootstrap. Most problems reveal themselves here:"],[288,"`blocksonly=1` tells `bitcoind` to skip relaying loose transactions\nduring the initial sync. It cuts bandwidth use significantly while\nthe node is chewing through history. You'll turn it off after the\nsync completes, alongside the `dbcache` reduction, see the bottom\nof this page."],[125,"`cd /home/bitcoin`"],[123,"`cd`"],[155,"`chmod +x script.sh`"],[153,"`chmod`"],[152,"`chown bitcoin:bitcoin myfile.txt`"],[150,"`chown`"],[131,"`cp file.txt newfile.txt`"],[129,"`cp`"],[246,"`Ctrl-C` to stop, then:"],[162,"`exit`"],[164,"`exit`"],[777,"`fail2ban` is a watchful little daemon that tails the SSH log and\nbans IP addresses that rack up failed logins. On Trixie there's a\nwrinkle: `rsyslog` is no longer installed by default, so `fail2ban`\nhas to read authentication events straight from the systemd journal.\nSounds fiddly, but it's two extra pieces and you're done."],[984,"`getinfo` should return an `identity_pubkey`, the current\n`block_height`, and `synced_to_chain: true` once LND has caught\nup with the graph. `getnetworkinfo` should show a non-zero\nnumber of nodes and channels, proof that LND is talking to the\nwider Lightning network over Tor."],[171,"`htop`"],[173,"`htop`"],[741,"`id_ed25519.pub`, the **public** key. This is what you hand to\nthe Pi (and any other server you want to reach)."],[740,"`id_ed25519`, the **private** key. This stays on your computer\nand nowhere else. Ever."],[1345,"`INDEXING_BLOCKS_AMOUNT: 0` disables historical address indexing on\nfirst run. Once the node is stable, raise it to `4320` (30 days) or\n`11000` (about 3 months) to unlock address balance history in the UI.\nRestart the service after changing it."],[168,"`journalctl`"],[143,"`ln -s /target /link`"],[141,"`ln -s`"],[1163,"`lnbalance` is a compact shell script by\nRobClark56 that prints a one-screen\nbalance summary for your Lightning node. It's handy when you want\nnumbers on-demand from the terminal without waiting on a heavier\ndashboard."],[1171,"`lnchannels` is a companion script by\nRobClark56 that prints a clean\noverview of all your Lightning channels and their state. It pairs\nwell with `lnbalance` for quick, terminal-only status checks on the\nnode."],[128,"`ls -la /data`"],[126,"`ls`"],[140,"`mkdir /home/bitcoin/new`"],[138,"`mkdir`"],[134,"`mv file.txt moved.txt`"],[132,"`mv`"],[158,"`nano textfile.txt`"],[156,"`nano`"],[1346,"`npm install` triggers a Rust compilation before installing Node.js packages.\nOn a Pi 5 that takes 5-10 minutes. Run the commands in a `tmux` or\n`screen` session."],[342,"`npm install` will print warnings about vulnerabilities in transitive\ndependencies. Read them, but don't panic. The explorer serves only\nto **you** on your LAN; the realistic threat surface is your own\nbrowser, not a remote attacker poking at the Express server. Don't\nblindly `npm audit fix`, it'll break things."],[137,"`rm tempfile.txt`"],[135,"`rm`"],[174,"`shutdown`"],[147,"`su`"],[170,"`sudo journalctl -u bitcoind`"],[146,"`sudo nano textfile.txt`"],[176,"`sudo shutdown -r now`"],[149,"`sudo su bitcoin`"],[167,"`sudo systemctl start bitcoind`"],[144,"`sudo`"],[165,"`systemctl`"],[161,"`tar -cvf a.tar file1.txt file2.txt`"],[159,"`tar`"],[363,"`tls internal` tells Caddy to mint and manage a self-signed\ncertificate from its own CA, no public DNS needed."],[956,"`tor.streamisolation=true` gives every outbound Lightning\nconnection its own Tor circuit, so two peers can't correlate you\nfrom the same exit. Good privacy default."],[772,"`ufw limit ssh` blocks any IP making six or more connection\nattempts within 30 seconds, a first layer of brute-force defence\non top of what `fail2ban` does below."],[894,"A **24-word seed** written down on paper and locked away, the\nonly rope back to your on-chain funds if the Pi dies."],[399,"A **hardware wallet** keeps private keys on a small dedicated\ndevice that never exposes them to your computer. Signing happens\non the device itself; your computer only sees the signed\ntransaction."],[397,"A **hot wallet** holds its private keys in plaintext on a device\nconnected to the internet. Fine for small amounts; dangerous for\nsavings."],[858,"A **path unit** watches a file. When the file changes, systemd\nactivates a matching **service unit**. The two go together."],[537,"A **Raspberry Pi 5** (or Pi 4) booting Debian 13 \"Trixie\" straight\nfrom a 2 TB USB SSD."],[847,"A **remote host** you trust, another machine on your LAN, a\nVPS you own, an always-on box at a friend's place, or a cheap\nhome NAS. Anywhere `ssh` can reach."],[596,"A **solid green** LED that never flickers usually means the Pi\ndidn't find anything bootable and is sitting there waiting."],[398,"A **watch-only wallet** holds only your *public* keys. It can\nshow balances, build transactions, and tell a hardware wallet\nwhat to sign, but it cannot spend anything without the hardware\nwallet present."],[104,"A 2 TB SSD. The blockchain is around 700 GB as of 2026, growing\nroughly 7 GB per month. The Electrs index adds another \\~70 GB, and\nthe OS takes \\~20 GB. A 1 TB drive is basically full on day one. See\nHardware for what to buy and\nwhich SSD enclosure chipsets to avoid."],[844,"A channel backup that lives on the same SSD as LND is no backup\nat all, the scenario it's meant to survive is the SSD dying. The\nwhole point of this page is to get a copy of `channel.backup` onto\na machine that isn't the Pi."],[66,"A community project"],[942,"A corrupt download trips the checksum. A compromised download\nserver serves a real binary with a **matching** checksum and a\nforged manifest. The signature check is what catches that, the\nattacker would also need Roasbeef's private key, which they do not\nhave."],[1340,"A dedicated system user limits the blast radius of any bug. Adding it\nto the `bitcoin` group lets Mempool authenticate to Bitcoin Core via\nthe cookie file, the same approach BTC RPC Explorer uses."],[811,"A fast SSD is non-negotiable. A slow drive drags the initial block\ndownload into the weekend and turns the Electrs index build into a\nslog. This is why it pays to benchmark now, before you've committed\na few hundred gigabytes of blockchain data to the wrong enclosure.\nThe Pi 5 handles USB 3 storage well, but some enclosures still\nunderperform, this is the moment to catch that."],[177,"A few hand-picked starting points that actually teach rather than\npitch:"],[1219,"A few RaspiBolt bonus tools (regolancer and some monitoring\nhelpers) are written in Go. This short guide handles\ninstalling, upgrading, and removing the Go toolchain on the Pi, so\nyou can build those tools yourself without polluting the rest of\nthe system."],[595,"A flickering **green** LED means the SSD is being read, exactly\nwhat you want. Boot takes 20-40 seconds on an SSD."],[70,"A full node is, in plain terms, your own personal goldsmith. When a\npayment arrives, your node verifies it from first principles: the\nsignatures, the scripts, the history, the supply cap. No trust, no\nmiddleman, no API key away from being cut off. If Bitcoin is digital\ngold, a full node is the set of scales you own and trust."],[1021,"A hidden service address is 56 random base32 characters, the\ninternet equivalent of an unlisted phone number. Anyone who\ndoesn't have the string cannot connect, cannot scan for it, and\ncannot even tell that your Pi exists as a Lightning endpoint.\nThat's a far stronger privacy position than opening port 8080 on\nyour router."],[277,"A matching SHA256 only proves the file matches the checksum file.\nThe GPG step is what proves the checksum file itself came from the\nBitcoin Core maintainers and not someone who also controls the\ndownload server. Verify both, or verify neither."],[791,"A node dedicated to Bitcoin has no use for Bluetooth, and if you're\nconnected over Ethernet, no use for Wi-Fi either. Turning off the\nradios you aren't using removes another slice of attack surface."],[388,"A node with no wallet is a useful thing, but it's not a personal\nthing. This page closes the loop: a wallet on your computer, talking\nto your node on the Pi, signing with a hardware wallet you hold in\nyour hand. That's the endgame, your keys, your node, your\nvalidation, your privacy."],[265,"A Pi 4 with 8 GB RAM still gets there, just slower, plan for five to\nseven days for the initial sync and keep the `dbcache` a little lower\n(see below). Anything less than 8 GB of RAM will struggle once LND\nand Electrs join the party; upgrade if you can."],[21,"A private web explorer for your own blockchain. Mempool, fees, block details, all without leaking queries to a third party."],[27,"A private WireGuard mesh between your devices. The Pi gets a stable `100.x.y.z` address that only your devices can reach."],[396,"A quick piece of framing before you install anything."],[228,"A red, broken symlink means the target directory doesn't exist,\ncreate `/data/bitcoin` (or `/data/lnd`) with the right ownership\nand re-link."],[539,"A running firewall (`ufw`) and brute-force protection (`fail2ban`)."],[734,"A selective reference of useful Linux commands lives in the\nFAQ, bookmark it."],[119,"A short reference for commands that show up repeatedly in this\nguide. For any specific one, `man <command>` has the full manual,\ntype `q` to exit."],[1215,"A small quality-of-life tweak: make your shell prompt shine with a\ngolden Bitcoin symbol, enable color output for `ls`, and nudge the\ndefaults so the terminal is easier on the eyes. Purely cosmetic, but\nit takes two minutes and you'll appreciate it every time you log\nback in."],[994,"A small reference you'll come back to:"],[594,"A solid **red** LED means the Pi is powered."],[1258,"A sudden power loss can corrupt the Bitcoin or LND database and\nforce a lengthy resync. With a UPS and\nNetwork UPS Tools (NUT), your node\nwatches the battery level and triggers a clean shutdown before the\nUPS runs out, turning a brownout into a five-minute nuisance\ninstead of hours of downtime."],[825,"A swapfile on an SSD wears the flash with every heavy swap burst,\nand on a microSD card it's painfully slow. `zram` sidesteps both:\npages are compressed and kept in RAM, so an 8 GB Pi effectively gets\na little more memory without ever touching the disk."],[507,"About the time commitment"],[738,"Accept the default file location by pressing Enter, and pick a\nstrong passphrase when prompted. The passphrase protects the key\nfile on disk, you'll type it once per session, and your OS\nkeychain can remember it after that."],[854,"Accept the fingerprint. You should see `ok`. Exit the `lnd`\nsession:"],[626,"Active cooler (official or compatible)"],[1004,"Add a hidden service for LND REST"],[1355,"Add a Mempool block to the Caddyfile (create the file first if Caddy\nwas not already installed from the BTC RPC Explorer guide):"],[1092,"Add a site block for RTL. The `tls internal` line tells Caddy\nto mint a cert from its own CA rather than trying Let's Encrypt\n(which won't work for a `.local` hostname anyway):"],[369,"Add a stanza to `/etc/tor/torrc`:"],[499,"Add a stanza to `/etc/tor/torrc`:"],[336,"Add NodeSource and install:"],[692,"Add Tailscale's apt repository, install the client, and start it:"],[1357,"Add the Mempool block after your existing blocks:"],[672,"Add the Tor Project's official repository rather than leaning on the\nDebian package, this way you get current Tor releases straight from\nupstream."],[922,"Add watchtowers"],[789,"Add:"],[1296,"Additional Bitcoin software, explorers, wallets, alternative Electrum servers, privacy tools, and testnet."],[40,"Address and transaction index"],[203,"admin, bitcoin, lnd users. Broken symlinks to /data. Permissions."],[260,"After the initial sync"],[1204,"Aliases"],[1207,"Aliases are shortcuts for long or frequently used shell commands.\nThe guide installs a curated `.bash_aliases` file so `admin` gets\nconcise shortcuts for inspecting Bitcoin Core, LND, system logs, and\nservice status, saving you the muscle memory of typing the full\ncommand every time."],[1005,"Allow LND REST on loopback"],[1083,"Also set `fiatConversion` to `true` if you want USD/EUR totals\nin the UI, and leave `Authentication → logoutRedirectLink`\nalone."],[294,"Also symlink the data directory into `admin`'s home so\n`bitcoin-cli` works without a `-datadir` flag:"],[1130,"Alternative Lightning implementation you can run instead of LND, or side-by-side with it on the same node."],[1149,"Alternative Lightning implementation you can run instead of or alongside LND."],[375,"Always skim the changelog\nfirst, breaking changes are rare but not unheard of."],[1109,"AmbossPing"],[1112,"AmbossPing is a small bash script that pings\namboss.space on a schedule to keep your node's\nmonitoring status fresh. Link your Telegram account to Amboss and\nyou'll receive push alerts whenever the ping status changes, without\nneeding ThunderHub or a heavier dashboard."],[897,"An **automated channel backup** that rsyncs your\n`channel.backup` file to an offsite host every time it changes."],[848,"An **SSH key** on the Pi that you've added to\n`~/.ssh/authorized_keys` on the remote host."],[1313,"Anonymous network layer alongside Tor for Bitcoin Core."],[1292,"Anonymous network layer you can run alongside Tor to give Bitcoin Core a second private transport."],[875,"Answer `y` to the \"existing cipher seed\" prompt and paste the\n24 words. When prompted for an SCB, point at `/tmp/channel.backup`."],[1031,"Anyone who can photograph this screen has full control of your\nLightning node. Don't screenshot it. Don't paste it into a chat.\nClose the terminal as soon as Zeus has paired."],[1073,"Anyone with `admin.macaroon` and network reach to LND's gRPC port\ncan open channels, close channels, and send payments. It is not\nthe seed, but it can drain active channels. Keep the file locked\ndown and do not commit it to any repository."],[975,"Anyone with these words can empty every on-chain sat on this\nnode. The seed does **not** restore Lightning channel balances,\nfor that, see Channel backup."],[816,"Anything above **100 MB/s** is fine for a full node. If you see\nnumbers below 50 MB/s, the enclosure is probably falling back to UAS\nmode with a buggy driver, a well-known problem with certain chipsets\n(hello again, JMicron). The\nFix bad USB3 performance\nsection in Troubleshooting walks through disabling UAS for a specific\ndrive."],[797,"apt full-upgrade, verify SSD speed with hdparm, create /data directory and service-user symlinks, confirm zram swap is active on Trixie."],[1,"Architecture"],[160,"archive tool"],[194,"Are the data symlinks pointing at `/data`?"],[191,"Are the right ports open on the firewall?"],[851,"As `admin`, become `lnd` and generate a key (no passphrase,\na passphrase would defeat unattended sync):"],[470,"As `admin`, clone the repo at a specific tag:"],[855,"As `admin`, create the script:"],[484,"As `admin`, create the unit file:"],[1086,"As `admin`, create the unit file:"],[271,"As `admin`, drop into `/tmp` (cleared on every reboot) and pull\nthe binary, the checksum file, and the signature file:"],[864,"As `admin`, follow the service journal in one SSH session:"],[980,"As `admin`, start the service and follow the log:"],[1106,"As `admin`, stop the service and become `rtl`:"],[281,"As the `bitcoin` user, fetch the helper script:"],[1067,"As user `admin`, add the NodeSource GPG key and apt source:"],[929,"As user `admin`, create the `lnd` user. Give it group membership\nin `bitcoin` (so it can read `bitcoin.conf` for auto-RPC) and in\n`debian-tor` (so it can read Tor's cookie file for the control\nport):"],[1017,"As user `admin`, open the Tor configuration:"],[1080,"As user `rtl`, still in `/home/rtl/RTL`:"],[299,"Ask the running node for its view of the chain:"],[533,"Assumptions"],[887,"Assumptions"],[966,"At the prompts:"],[217,"At the start of the line, add `usb-storage.quirks=VENDOR:PRODUCT:u`\nwith your values, keep the single space before whatever follows:"],[1126,"Automated channel and liquidity manager for Core Lightning that opens, rebalances, and re-prices channels on its own."],[1151,"Automated channel and liquidity manager for Core Lightning."],[827,"Automated off-Pi sync of channel.backup (SCB, static channel backup) via systemd.path and scp. Restore flow with lncli restorechanbackup if the SSD dies."],[1330,"Autostart on boot"],[1350,"Back as user `admin`, create the service file:"],[959,"Back as user `admin`, create the unit file:"],[241,"Back in the first session, LND continues: loads the wallet,\nconnects to `bitcoind` via ZMQ, starts rescanning, and eventually\nlogs `Chain backend is fully synced`. Any configuration or\nconnectivity errors show up in this output."],[978,"Back in the first window where `lnd` is still running, stop it with\n`Ctrl-C`. Then start it again in the foreground to confirm the\nauto-unlock works:"],[853,"Back on the **Pi** as `lnd`, do the first connection by hand\nso the remote host's fingerprint lands in `known_hosts`:"],[585,"Back on the main screen, the Imager asks &#x2A;*\"Use OS customisation?\"*&#x2A;.\nClick &#x2A;*\"YES\"*&#x2A;. Read the final warning, confirm you picked the\nright drive, and click &#x2A;*\"YES\"** again to start writing."],[89,"Back up LND before you start"],[60,"Backstory"],[1113,"Balance of Satoshis"],[1116,"Balance of Satoshis\n(BoS) is a CLI toolkit for LND from Alex Bosworth. Its rebalancing\ncommand is the headline feature, but BoS bundles dozens of other\nutilities, node monitoring, Telegram bot integration, payment\nrouting inspection, that extend what you can do beyond `lncli`."],[890,"Because Bitcoin's base layer is deliberately slow and deliberately\nexpensive. Every transaction lands in a block that thousands of\nnodes worldwide will validate and store forever, and that's exactly\nwhat you want for settling serious money, not for buying a coffee.\nThe **Lightning Network** is the second layer that fixes the coffee\nproblem: payments settle in milliseconds, cost fractions of a cent,\nand only touch the base chain when a channel opens or closes."],[950,"Become `lnd` again and create the password file, then enter\npassword `[C]` (one you haven't used anywhere else):"],[1074,"Become the `rtl` user, clone the repo, and check out the pinned\nrelease tag:"],[352,"Before handing it to systemd, start it manually to shake out any\nconfig mistakes:"],[758,"Before touching anything, open a **second** SSH session in a new\nterminal window and confirm it logs in **without** asking for\npassword \\[A]. Leave that second session open while you make the\nchanges, if something goes sideways, you still have a working shell\nto undo it. Seriously. You don't want to learn this the hard way."],[615,"Before you boot a single terminal, get the hardware sorted and pick\nyour passwords. Five minutes of prep saves an hour of hunting for a\nmissing cable later, and keeps you from inventing a password on the\nfly when you should be paying attention."],[187,"Before you start digging"],[1304,"Beginner-friendly companion app for the BitBox02."],[1272,"Beginner-friendly desktop wallet for the BitBox02 hardware wallet, pointed at your own node."],[881,"Best-case recovery is the one you don't need: close your channels\non your own terms **before** decommissioning a node. A cooperative\nclose settles at the latest state with both peers agreeing,\ndoesn't trigger commit-delay timeouts, and pays lower on-chain\nfees. Planning to retire the Pi or move to new hardware?"],[1267,"Bisq"],[1270,"Bisq is a decentralized bitcoin exchange, a\ndesktop application that offers a private, censorship-resistant way\nto swap bitcoin for national currencies and other cryptocurrencies\nover the internet. Pointing Bisq at your own node keeps transaction\nlookups off third-party servers."],[1271,"BitBoxApp"],[57,"Bitcoin — Bitcoin Core, Electrs, BTC RPC Explorer, Sparrow."],[1295,"Bitcoin bonus"],[249,"Bitcoin client"],[518,"Bitcoin client, install Bitcoin\nCore 30.2, verify the release, tune the config\nfor a Pi 5, start syncing."],[14,"Bitcoin Core"],[195,"Bitcoin Core"],[269,"Bitcoin Core defaults to `~/.bitcoin` inside the user's home. On\nthis node the chain lives under `/data/bitcoin` on the SSD, a\nseparate mount you carved out in System configuration.\nA symlink from `/home/bitcoin/.bitcoin` to that location keeps the\ndefaults happy while the actual data sits on the fast disk."],[115,"Bitcoin Core doesn't need a backup, it can download and verify the\nentire chain from scratch. That takes a few days on a Pi, so if you\nwant to skip the resync, `rsync` the old `bitcoin` data directory\nacross from the old drive before you point the new node at it."],[1306,"Bitcoin Core GUI focused on multisig with hardware wallets."],[263,"Bitcoin Core is the reference client for\nthe Bitcoin network. It downloads the entire blockchain, validates\nevery transaction since the genesis block, and from then on holds\nthe authoritative answer to \"is this UTXO real?\", no third party\nasked, no trust extended. Everything else in this guide, Electrs,\nLightning, the block explorer, is a consumer of this node."],[308,"Bitcoin Core now uses its default \\~450 MB cache and relays\ntransactions in addition to blocks."],[302,"Bitcoin Core on the RaspiBolt is **not** where you should store\nfunds, the Electrum server and Sparrow Wallet in the next pages\nare. If you do create a wallet here for testing, the file lives at\n`/data/bitcoin/wallets/<name>/wallet.dat`. Copy it to an encrypted\nUSB stick before you load any real sats into it. The Pi is a node,\nnot a vault."],[274,"Bitcoin Core releases are signed by multiple maintainers through\nthe guix.sigs repository.\nImport all current signing keys in one sweep:"],[644,"Bitcoin Core RPC password"],[680,"Bitcoin Core will talk to the Tor daemon through Tor's **control\nport**. Enable that port and allow cookie-based authentication so\nlocal services can use it without a password."],[69,"Bitcoin is doing something quietly revolutionary: it lets you hold\nmoney that nobody else can freeze, inflate, or quietly reassign.\nThat only works if **the network stays decentralised**, if enough\nof us run our own full nodes to enforce the rules rather than\ntrusting somebody else to tell us what the rules are."],[180,"Bitcoin resources\nand Lightning resources\nby Jameson Lopp."],[72,"Bitcoin's base layer is deliberately slow and deliberately expensive.\nThat's a feature, not a bug, a genuinely decentralised blockchain\nis a scarce resource, and it cannot scale to every coffee purchase\non the planet without breaking exactly the property that makes it\nvaluable."],[648,"Block explorer password (optional)"],[312,"Blockchain explorer"],[520,"Blockchain explorer, install\nBTC RPC Explorer on Node.js 22, proxy it through Caddy, view your\nown chain."],[542,"Bluetooth and unused Wi-Fi radios switched off."],[523,"Bonus"],[1234,"Boot from microSD and use the external drive for data."],[1208,"Boot from microSD card"],[605,"Boot the Pi from this microSD card. When the green LED blinks\nsteadily, disconnect power, remove the microSD, and reboot with\nthe SSD attached."],[1209,"Boot the Raspberry Pi from microSD while using the external drive for blockchain and application data."],[560,"Boot your Pi"],[693,"Bring the Pi onto your tailnet. This prints a one-time URL,\nopen it on any device, log in (a personal Tailscale account is\nfree for up to 100 devices), and authorise the Pi:"],[1232,"Browser dashboard with links to all your web services."],[1221,"Browser-based dashboard with quick links to every web service running on your node."],[1138,"Browser-based LND node manager."],[1157,"Browser-based UI from Lightning Labs for managing LND channel liquidity with Loop and Pool."],[753,"Brute-force protection (fail2ban)"],[20,"BTC RPC Explorer"],[328,"BTC RPC Explorer is\na small, database-free web UI by Daniel McNally. It talks to your\nBitcoin Core over RPC and to Electrs for address balance queries,\ngives you a clean browser interface for blocks, transactions,\nmempool, and fee estimates, and never phones home."],[1070,"BTC RPC Explorer uses the same NodeSource setup. If Node 22 is\nalready present, skip this whole section."],[898,"Budget roughly **two to three hours** of hands-on time, most of it\nwaiting for `npm install` and your first channel to confirm."],[871,"Build a new Pi following the earlier sections. Get to the\npoint where LND is installed, `lnd.conf` is in place, and the\nservice is enabled, but **do not** run `lncli create` yet."],[448,"Build dependencies"],[449,"Build Electrs from source"],[446,"Build Electrs from source, index the blockchain for Electrum-protocol wallets, wrap the raw TCP port in TLS with stunnel so Sparrow, Electrum, and hardware wallets can connect privately."],[475,"Build it. On a Pi 5 this takes somewhere between 30 minutes and\nan hour; the Pi will work hard, and that's fine:"],[1328,"Build the backend"],[1329,"Build the frontend"],[1029,"Build the Zeus config URL and render it as a QR code in the\nterminal. The `lndconnect://` scheme is what Zeus expects:"],[1006,"Build the Zeus connect QR"],[957,"But `skip-proxy-for-clearnet-targets=true` is also on, which keeps\nlocal clearnet connections, like the one to `bitcoind` on\n`127.0.0.1:8332`, off of Tor entirely. Without that, LND tries to\nsend RPC calls through Tor to a localhost IP, and Tor (rightly)\nrefuses. The combination gives you Tor for everything public and\ndirect sockets for everything local."],[687,"But not every byte of traffic is routed through Tor yet. What\nyou've done is open the door, applications that