,"Fulcrum is a fast SPV server\nfor Bitcoin, Bitcoin Cash, and Litecoin written in C++ by Calin\nCulianu. Independent benchmarks rank it as one of the quickest\nElectrum server implementations available, which makes it a solid\nalternative to Electrs when you want lower query latency."],[995,"Full API reference at\napi.lightning.community."],[37,"Full blockchain and UTXO set"],[79,"Full list on github.com/raspibolt/raspibolt/graphs/contributors."],[921,"Fund the node and open a channel"],[1082,"Further down in the `nodes` → `settings` block, point RTL at\nLND on loopback. Leave the URLs as-is if the sample already\nuses `127.0.0.1`; change `localhost` to `127.0.0.1` if you see\nit, Node 18+ resolves `localhost` via IPv6 first, which LND\ndoesn't listen on:"],[986,"Generate a native-SegWit address and send a small amount of\non-chain sats to it from another wallet:"],[256,"Generate RPC credentials"],[712,"Generate the key pair"],[609,"Get the hardware sorted and pick your passwords before you boot anything."],[214,"Get the vendor and product IDs for the adapter:"],[689,"Getting into the Pi from the sofa is easy, it's on your LAN. Getting\ninto it from a café, a friend's house, or another country is\ntraditionally a pain: port forwarding, dynamic DNS, firewall\njuggling, and a stable home IP you probably don't have."],[599,"Grab a microSD card (any size, the data is erased)."],[1027,"Grab the admin macaroon as uppercase hex:"],[1028,"Grab the onion hostname:"],[112,"Grab the static channel backup file too, it's cheap insurance\nagainst anything going wrong with the full directory restore."],[1238,"Graceful shutdown when a connected UPS runs low."],[1244,"Greet yourself on SSH login with a one-screen status dashboard of Bitcoin, Lightning, and system health."],[465,"Hands-on setup is about 30 minutes. The slow part comes after: once\n`electrs` starts, it reads the whole chain from `bitcoind` and builds\nits own address index. On a Pi 5 with NVMe that's roughly **8 to 12\nhours**; on a Pi 4 with USB SSD it can stretch past a day. The Pi\nwill feel sluggish while it runs, disk I/O is the bottleneck.\nNothing to babysit, check back the next day. Make sure Bitcoin Core\nis fully synced (`verificationprogress` at 1.0) before you start,\notherwise `electrs` will happily index a moving target and thrash."],[56,"Hardware — Pi, SSD, OS, SSH, firewall, Tor, Tailscale."],[188,"Hardware and operating system"],[193,"Have the application users been created?"],[1307,"Headless Sparrow for systems without a display."],[1376,"Headless version of Sparrow Wallet intended for systems without a display, usable as a server daemon."],[1143,"Health-check pings to amboss.space."],[67,"Hey, I'm Stadicus. I wrote the first version of\nthis guide back in 2017, when Lightning was still pretty obscure, the\nmainnet wasn't even live yet, and running a node meant stringing\ntogether a hundred half-documented commands you hoped someone on\nReddit had gotten right. I love to tinker and build things, so I\nwrote down what worked, put it on Medium, and moved it to GitHub\nwhen it outgrew a single blog post."],[1220,"Homer"],[1223,"Homer is a simple\nbrowser-based dashboard for your self-hosted services. You list your\nweb tools in a YAML file and Homer renders a clean, bookmarkable\nhomepage, one click into RTL, ThunderHub, Mempool, BTC RPC\nExplorer, or whatever else you've spun up."],[379,"Hot wallet, watch-only, and why hardware matters"],[2,"How Bitcoin Core, Electrs, LND, RTL, Tor, Tailscale, and Caddy fit together on one Raspberry Pi."],[97,"How do I give the Pi a fixed IP address?"],[94,"How do I update Bitcoin Core or LND?"],[84,"How long does the initial blockchain sync take?"],[87,"How much disk space do I need?"],[322,"HTTPS on the LAN with Caddy"],[1331,"HTTPS on the LAN with Caddy"],[1291,"I2P"],[1294,"I2P, the Invisible Internet Protocol, is\nan anonymous, end-to-end encrypted network layer where peers never\nsee each other's real IP addresses. The guide installs\ni2pd, a C++ I2P daemon, so Bitcoin\nCore can reach peers over I2P in addition to clearnet and Tor."],[723,"If `ping` fails, mDNS (the `.local` name-discovery magic) isn't\nworking on your network, a common quirk of some routers. The\nofficial Raspberry Pi guide\nshows how to find the IP directly on your router or with `nmap`.\nOnce you have the IP (say `192.168.0.20`), use it wherever this guide\nsays `raspibolt.local`."],[59,"If anything on the map surprised you, the matching install page has\nthe why and the how."],[278,"If checksum and signature are happy, extract and install:"],[1369,"If MariaDB is no longer needed:"],[231,"If something's wrong with `bitcoind`, the quickest way to see what\nis to run it in the foreground, attached to a terminal, where the\nstartup output is visible."],[390,"If Sparrow doesn't fit your workflow, these are all fine companions\nto a RaspiBolt:"],[211,"If SSH refuses to let you in, wrong key, mistyped password,\nfail2ban banned you from your own LAN, plug a display and\nkeyboard into the Pi and log in locally. From there, fix the\nsshd config, unban yourself (`sudo fail2ban-client set sshd\nunbanip 192.168.x.x`), or add a new authorised key."],[210,"If the answer isn't in any of those, file a new issue and include\nenough detail that someone can reproduce the problem: what you did,\nwhat you expected, what you saw, and the output of any relevant\ncommands."],[597,"If the green LED is flickering, you're in business. Move on to the\nnext page. Done."],[794,"If the Pi is connected by Ethernet cable, also disable Wi-Fi:"],[879,"If the SCB you restore from is older than what your peers\nactually have, LND will ask for a close at an outdated state.\nWell-behaved peers will still close at the latest state they\nknow about (to their own benefit), and the amount you get back\nis whatever the **peer** says you should, not whatever you\nthought the balance was."],[408,"If the signature check fails, stop. Don't install. Ask on Sparrow's\nTelegram before doing anything else, this is not the moment to\ngive a random binary your seed words."],[607,"If USB boot still doesn't work after reflashing, the drive or\nenclosure is most likely the problem, see\nTroubleshooting for known-good chipsets\nand workarounds."],[775,"If you ever lock yourself out (wrong SSH port, busted config),\nattach a keyboard and screen to the Pi, log in locally, and fix the\nrules. Not fun, but always possible."],[1051,"If you ever want to pull the plug on Zeus pairing, phone lost,\nswitching apps, retiring the node, comment out the three hidden\nservice lines in `/etc/tor/torrc`:"],[103,"If you just need to copy files off the drive once, plugging it into\nanother Linux box, or the Pi itself, is usually the path of least\nresistance."],[766,"If you lose your private key, recovery means attaching a keyboard\nand screen to the Pi. Keep a copy of `~/.ssh/id_ed25519` somewhere\nsafe, an encrypted USB stick, or a password manager that supports\nfile attachments."],[652,"If you need inspiration for strong but memorable passwords, the\nfamous xkcd \"Password Strength\" comic is\nfunnier than this guide and still correct."],[770,"If you see `ERROR: Couldn't determine iptables version`, reboot\nthe Pi once after installing `ufw` and carry on."],[588,"If you skipped the Wi-Fi settings, connect an Ethernet cable."],[516,"If you want the big picture first, Architecture\nshows how Bitcoin Core, Electrs, and the block explorer fit together\nwith the rest of the stack."],[903,"If you want to see where LND plugs into everything else before\ndiving in, Architecture has the full picture."],[1242,"If you'd rather run RaspiBolt on different hardware, this guide\nadapts the setup to the Odroid XU4\nand compatible boards like the HC1 and HC2. The main guide's\nsoftware choices still apply, only the OS bring-up and a handful\nof platform-specific tweaks change."],[436,"If you're connecting over the LAN (`raspibolt.local` or IP), tell\nSparrow to