orage\"** and pick\nyour external SSD. Double-check, this drive will be wiped."],[866,"In the first session you should see\n`Started Sync LND channel.backup to offsite host`, the scp\nlines, and a clean exit."],[566,"In the Imager you'll also see Raspberry Pi OS based on Debian 12\n\"Bookworm\" under the **Legacy** menu. Don't pick it, this guide\ntargets Trixie."],[696,"In the Tailscale admin console,\nenable **MagicDNS**. Your Pi then becomes reachable as\n`raspibolt.<your-tailnet>.ts.net` from any other device on the\ntailnet, no more memorising `100.x.y.z`. You can also give it a\ncustom short name from the same console."],[17,"Indexes Bitcoin Core's data so wallets can ask \"what's the balance of this address?\" in milliseconds."],[778,"Install `fail2ban` and the Python bindings for the systemd journal:"],[809,"Install `git`, you'll need it later to clone source code:"],[812,"Install `hdparm`, a classic disk benchmarking tool:"],[1026,"Install `qrencode` for the QR render, and `xxd` for the macaroon\nhex/base64 conversion below. On Debian 13, `xxd` is its own\npackage and isn't pulled in by default:"],[676,"Install `tor` along with the Tor Project's keyring package (which\nkeeps the signing key up to date automatically):"],[769,"Install `ufw`:"],[911,"Install and configure LND (Lightning Network Daemon). Write lnd.conf for bitcoind RPC and ZMQ, generate the 24-word seed, set up auto-unlock, enable watchtower and wumbo channels."],[407,"Install and launch Sparrow."],[250,"Install and run Bitcoin Core (bitcoind), GPG-verify the release, tune bitcoin.conf for a Pi 5 (dbcache, maxmempool), and sync the full blockchain (IBD, initial block download) through Tor."],[437,"Install and start Tor on the computer:"],[505,"Install Bitcoin Core, Electrs, and a block explorer, then point a desktop wallet at your own node."],[318,"Install BTC RPC Explorer"],[1324,"Install build dependencies"],[323,"Install Caddy"],[1216,"Install Go"],[885,"Install LND, wire up a web dashboard and mobile app, and keep your channels safe."],[1326,"Install Mempool"],[1068,"Install Node and verify:"],[1056,"Install Node.js 22"],[316,"Install Node.js 22 LTS"],[329,"Install Node.js 22 LTS from NodeSource."],[1077,"Install production dependencies. This pulls a few hundred\npackages and can take ten minutes or more, the process\noccasionally appears frozen on a single package, it's fine:"],[556,"Install Raspberry Pi Imager"],[1058,"Install RTL"],[461,"Install Rust so you can build Electrs, the project doesn't ship\nprebuilt binaries for ARM."],[380,"Install Sparrow"],[454,"Install stunnel"],[666,"Install Tailscale on the Pi"],[697,"Install Tailscale on whatever device you want to SSH **from**:"],[255,"Install the binaries"],[915,"Install the binaries"],[655,"Install the latest firmware update for the router."],[476,"Install the resulting binary to `/usr/local/bin`:"],[663,"Install Tor"],[1032,"Install Zeus on your phone.\nzeusln.app has the direct links, Apple\nApp Store, Google Play, F-Droid, or a direct APK download if\nyou prefer to sideload."],[1217,"Install, update, or uninstall the Go toolchain, which several bonus tools require."],[1233,"Install, update, or uninstall the Go toolchain."],[264,"Installing `bitcoind` is a short job. Syncing it is not. On a Pi 5\nwith a good USB 3 SSD (or NVMe via the M.2 HAT+), the initial block\ndownload takes roughly **two to five days**. You don't have to sit\nwith it, start it, check in once a day, come back when\n`verificationprogress` is a hair below 1."],[759,"Instead of editing the main `sshd_config` (which gets rewritten\non package updates), drop a small override file into the\n`sshd_config.d/` directory, that's the modern Debian way:"],[1250,"Instead of trusting a plain SSH key on your laptop, you can let a\nTrezor hardware wallet sign SSH challenges. Your key never leaves\nthe device, and every login prompts you to physically confirm on\nthe Trezor, a meaningful bump in security for the admin account\nthat runs your node."],[1177,"Interactive text-mode channel viewer for Lightning nodes, inspired by htop."],[1140,"Interactive text-mode channel viewer."],[1154,"iOS Lightning wallet pointed at your node."],[1201,"iOS Lightning wallet that connects to your RaspiBolt over the local network for peer, channel, and payment management."],[561,"Is it alive?"],[839,"It does **not** re-open your channels. It does **not** give you\naccess to off-chain liquidity on a fresh node. What it does, on\nrestore, is send a request to every channel peer asking them to\nforce-close the channel at the latest state they know about. Your\nfunds then land in your on-chain wallet after the usual\ncommit-timeout."],[68,"It hasn't been \"my own\" guide for a long time. Dozens of contributors\nhave shaped it over the years. RaspiBolt is a community project now,\nand the community keeps it honest."],[565,"It's based on &#x2A;*Debian 13 \"Trixie\"**, the current Debian stable\nrelease (since August 2025) and the same OS that powers a good slice\nof the internet's servers. Trixie gets security updates well into\nthe 2030s. Because the guide only uses standard Debian commands,\neverything you learn here also applies to other Debian machines."],[1259,"JAM (JoinMarket UI)"],[1262,"JAM is a web interface for\nJoinMarket that aims to make CoinJoin accessible to non-expert users.\nIt ships sensible defaults and a browser-based UI while still\nexposing the advanced knobs experienced JoinMarket users rely on."],[1316,"JoinMarket"],[1319,"JoinMarket\nis a decentralized marketplace for CoinJoin transactions. Running it\non your node lets you either mix your own coins by paying a small\nfee or become a liquidity maker and earn sats for providing the\ninputs others use to mix."],[186,"Jump to the thing that's on fire"],[593,"Keep an eye on the two LEDs on the Pi:"],[868,"Keep the first session running for the first real channel\nopen or close. When LND updates the SCB for real, you should\nsee a fresh sync event land the same way."],[503,"Keep the old binary around until the new one has served traffic\nfor a few hours, rolling back is as simple as copying\n`electrs.old` back on top."],[658,"Keep your phone and laptop patched and protected with a screen\nlock."],[806,"Keeping the system patched is table stakes. Debian's `apt` package\nmanager handles OS updates and application upgrades in the same\ncommand."],[736,"Key pairs sound like a cryptography homework assignment, but the\nworkflow is mechanical: run one command, copy one file. This guide\nuses **Ed25519** keys. They're short, fast, and well supported by\nevery current SSH client and server."],[639,"Label"],[384,"Label your UTXOs"],[309,"Later in this guide you'll verify signatures on LND, Electrs, and\nother software. Those projects ship OpenTimestamps proofs for their\nrelease files, cryptographic evidence that a given file existed\nbefore a particular Bitcoin block. Your node can verify those proofs\nagainst its own chain data, so you're not trusting a third-party\ntimestamp server."],[163,"leave current shell"],[982,"Let `admin` use `lncli` without `sudo`. The `admin` user is\nalready in the `lnd` group; the remaining permissions tweak is\na symlink and a group-read bit on the macaroon:"],[1097,"Let's Encrypt needs a public DNS name and an internet-reachable\nport 80 or a DNS-01 challenge. Your home node has neither, and\npublishing the RTL dashboard on the open internet is not something\nthis guide recommends. Caddy's internal CA produces a perfectly\ngood TLS cert; the browser warning is a one-time \"I trust this\nhost on my LAN\" click. If you want a trusted cert for your LAN,\nuse DNS-01 with a real domain you own, but that's a separate\nbonus guide."],[58,"Lightning — LND, RTL, Zeus, channel backup."],[1133,"Lightning bonus"],[991,"Lightning channels assume both sides are honest. If a peer tries\nto settle an old channel state while your node is offline, they\nwalk away with funds that should have been yours. Watchtowers are\nthird-party nodes that watch your channels for you and punish\ncheaters, and because the worst a watchtower can do is fail\nsilently, you don't have to trust them."],[910,"Lightning client"],[905,"Lightning client, download,\nverify, and run LND 0.20.1-beta; create the wallet and seed;\nset up auto-unlock."],[1122,"Lightning firewall that protects LND from HTLC-flooding griefing attacks."],[927,"Lightning isn't a testbed. The wallet you create here holds real\nbitcoin, and every channel open or close is an on-chain transaction\nthat costs real fees. Until you have your 24-word seed **written\ndown on paper** and your `channel.backup` file syncing off-Pi\n(next page after this one), don't fund the wallet. A lost seed or\nmissing SCB on a dead SSD means the funds are gone, no support desk.\nBudget about **30 minutes** of hands-on time for this page."],[1152,"Lightning Labs UI for Loop and Pool."],[1156,"Lightning Terminal"],[1159,"Lightning Terminal\nis a web UI from Lightning Labs that helps LND operators manage\nchannel liquidity through the commercial Loop and Pool services. It\nbundles those services in a single interface and is useful if you\nwant managed submarine swaps or liquidity leases without writing\nscripts."],[1150,"Lightning wallet and accounts system with extensions."],[646,"Lightning wallet password (LND)"],[1309,"Lightweight Electrum server that indexes only your wallets."],[1280,"Lightweight Electrum server that serves only your own wallets, as an alternative to Electrs or Fulcrum."],[1148,"Lightweight LND rebalancer in Go."],[1185,"Lightweight LND rebalancer written in Go, focused on fast and efficient circular rebalances."],[1173,"Lightweight web GUI for power users to monitor and automate LND routing-node operations."],[478,"Like `bitcoind`, Electrs runs as its own user with no shell password\nand a tidy data directory on the SSD."],[421,"Linux: `~/.sparrow/certs`"],[439,"Linux: `sudo apt install tor && sudo systemctl enable --now tor`\n(port 9050)."],[127,"list directory contents"],[172,"live process and resource view"],[1160,"lnbalance"],[1164,"LNbits"],[1167,"LNbits is a free and open-source\nLightning wallet and accounts system. It sits on top of your node\nand lets you carve out sub-wallets with their own balances, APIs,\nand third-party integrations, handy for splitting a family node,\npowering a point of sale, or experimenting with LN extensions."],[1168,"lnchannels"],[18,"LND"],[196,"LND"],[928,"LND is a long-running daemon that manages real money. It gets its\nown unprivileged system user and a dedicated data directory on the\nSSD, with the home-directory `~/.lnd` path symlinked to the real\nlocation. Same pattern you used for `bitcoind`."],[1048,"LND is locked (password-file auto-unlock didn't trigger).\nCheck `sudo systemctl status lnd` and look for\n`Opened wallet`."],[1144,"LND power-user toolkit for rebalancing and monitoring."],[1114,"LND power-user toolkit for rebalancing channels, monitoring the node, and driving a Telegram bot."],[970,"LND prints a 24-word cipher seed. &#x2A;*Stop scrolling. Read this\npart.**"],[952,"LND reads its configuration from `/data/lnd/lnd.conf` (resolved\nvia the `~/.lnd` symlink). This file does the heavy lifting,\nchain backend, Tor, channel policy, watchtower client, all of it."],[996,"LND release notes are non-negotiable reading, some releases ship\ndatabase migrations that are one-way. Before every upgrade:"],[1045,"LND REST isn't on `127.0.0.1:8080`: `sudo ss -tulpn | grep 8080`."],[934,"LND ships as a statically linked binary tarball. You'll download\nit, verify the SHA256 checksum, verify the GPG signature on the\nmanifest, and only then copy the binaries into place."],[114,"LND should come up with your existing wallet, peers, and channels."],[240,"LND will start, then pause waiting for you to unlock the wallet.\nIn a **second SSH session**, unlock it:"],[247,"LND's log lives in `/data/lnd/logs/bitcoin/mainnet/lnd.log`, tail\nit the same way:"],[1022,"LND's REST API already listens on `127.0.0.1:8080` by default;\nthe hidden service above forwards the onion's port 8080 to that\nloopback socket, so nothing new needs to open on the firewall."],[946,"LND's wallet is password-protected and asks for the password on\nevery startup. You have two options:"],[1172,"LNDg"],[1175,"LNDg is a lightweight web\ninterface for LND aimed at routing-node operators. It surfaces\nchannel and forwarding data and can automate rebalancing, fee\nadjustments, and channel opens so you spend less time manually\nrunning `lncli` commands."],[1176,"lntop"],[1179,"lntop is an interactive,\ntext-mode channels viewer for Lightning nodes on Unix systems. If\nyou live in the terminal, it gives you a compact, keyboard-driven\noverview of channel state and flow without spinning up a browser."],[287,"Lock the file down so only `bitcoin` and its group can read it,\nthe `rpcauth` hash isn't exactly a secret, but it's a credential:"],[951,"Lock the file down so only `lnd` can read it:"],[798,"Log back in"],[725,"Log in with &#x2A;*password \\[A]**, the one you set in the Imager."],[1096,"Log in with password `[E]`."],[702,"Log in with the same account. Once both devices are on the tailnet,\nSSH to the Pi's tailnet IP (or MagicDNS name if you enabled it):"],[983,"Log out of the SSH session and log back in, group membership\nonly takes effect on a fresh shell. Then smoke-test:"],[1229,"Login dashboard with node and system status."],[979,"Look for `Attempting automatic wallet unlock with password` and\n`Opened wallet`. Stop it again with `Ctrl-C` and exit the `lnd`\nuser session:"],[1076,"Look for `Good signature from \"saubyk\"`. The primary key\nfingerprint is `3E9B D443 6C28 8039 CA82 7A92 00C9 E2BC 2E45 666F`."],[941,"Look for a `Good signature from \"Olaoluwa Osuntokun\"` line. The\nfull fingerprint should read\n`A5B6 1896 952D 9FDA 83BC 054C DC42 612E 8923 7182`. GPG will\nalso warn that the key isn't certified with a trusted signature.\nThat's expected; you haven't built a web of trust around this\nkey, you've just pinned its fingerprint."],[1047,"Macaroon is malformed. Regenerate the QR with the exact\ncommands above; the base64url encoding matters."],[420,"macOS: `~/.sparrow/certs`"],[438,"macOS: `brew install tor && brew services start tor` (SOCKS\non port 9050), or run Tor Browser (SOCKS on port 9150)."],[139,"make directory"],[857,"Make it executable:"],[773,"Make sure `ufw` comes up at boot, and check the active rules:"],[788,"Make sure PAM actually applies those limits on login. Open each\nof these files and add a `pam_limits.so` line, right before any\ntrailing comment:"],[142,"make symlink"],[642,"Master user password (`admin` login)"],[1030,"Maximise your terminal window and shrink the font with\n`Ctrl`-`-` until the whole QR fits on screen."],[814,"Measure raw read throughput:"],[1320,"Mempool Explorer"],[1334,"Mempool is the same open-source\ncode that runs mempool.space, self-hosted on your own node. Transaction\nlookups, fee estimates, and UTXO queries stay on your LAN and never\nreach a third party."],[1341,"Mempool's backend includes a Rust-native block-template builder (GBT).\nDebian 13 Trixie ships Rust 1.85, which meets the 1.84 requirement:"],[1252,"Migrate from a smaller to a larger external drive as the blockchain outgrows your current storage."],[1235,"Migrate your node data to a larger drive."],[455,"Mint a self-signed certificate"],[1002,"Mobile app"],[907,"Mobile app, set up a Tor hidden\nservice for LND's REST API and pair the Zeus phone app with it."],[133,"move or rename"],[93,"My node was offline for a few days. What now?"],[270,"Never run a Bitcoin binary you haven't verified. The point of a\nfull node is to trust your own software, which means the software\nhas to be what the developers actually signed."],[469,"No binaries, no shortcuts: you build from a signed tag. That's the\nonly way to know the thing running on your node matches what the\nmaintainer, Roman Zeyde, actually\nreleased."],[9,"No commands here. The install steps live in the sections that\nfollow. This is strictly orientation."],[230,"No error means the permissions are correct."],[631,"No microSD card? Correct, you'll boot the operating system directly\nfrom the SSD. It's faster, more reliable, and one fewer component to\nlose."],[763,"No output means the file is valid."],[101,"Nobody really knows. Probably not. Routing fees on a well-placed\nnode cover electricity and a bit of the hardware, not much more.\nRun a Lightning node because you want payments to work, not\nbecause you want a yield-bearing business. Enjoy the ride."],[1337,"Node.js 22 installed (from the BTC RPC Explorer guide or standalone via `nodesource.com`)"],[637,"Not a Pi person? The guide sticks to standard Debian, which means it\nalso runs happily on other Debian 13 machines, a cloud server, a VM\non your laptop, an Intel NUC, or another ARM board. The shell\ncommands are identical; only the hardware chapters differ."],[633,"Not all USB-to-SATA enclosures play well with the Pi. The ones\nbased on **JMicron** chipsets (JMS578, JMS580, JMS583 and friends)\nare a long-running source of reset loops, dropped connections, and\nfailed boots."],[105,"Not cleanly. v4 is built on Debian 13 \"Trixie\" with a different\npackage set, a different reverse proxy, and a different layout for\nsecrets and data directories. The safest upgrade is a **fresh\ninstall**, then restore the parts that are hard to recreate."],[1211,"Not every Raspberry Pi can boot directly from an external drive. If\nyours can't, or your USB-SATA enclosure is picky, this guide sets\nup a split configuration: boot the OS from a microSD card, then mount\nthe external drive for all the application and blockchain data."],[378,"Not Sparrow?"],[117,"Nothing special. Bitcoin Core picks up from where it stopped and\ncatches up with the chain. LND reconnects to channel peers\nautomatically. Give it 30-60 minutes after startup before worrying\nabout anything. Lightning channels stay safe while your node is\noffline. They just can't route or send payments while it's down."],[1239,"Odroid setup"],[622,"Official **27W USB-C PD** power supply"],[679,"Older Tor install guides want you to `apt install apt-transport-https`\nfirst. On Trixie that package is a no-op, HTTPS support is built\ninto `apt` itself. Skip it with a clear conscience."],[743,"On **macOS or Linux**, one command does it:"],[745,"On **Windows**, `ssh-copy-id` isn't shipped by default. Run this\none-liner in PowerShell instead, it pipes your public key over SSH\nand sets the right permissions on the Pi:"],[592,"On a **Pi 4**, USB boot is enabled by default on any board shipped\nafter September 2020. If your Pi 4 is older and refuses to boot\nfrom the SSD, see the section below on fixing the bootloader."],[824,"On an 8 GB Pi 5, the default 2 GB zram swap is plenty."],[817,"On NVMe the device is `/dev/nvme0n1`, not `/dev/sda`. You can skip\nthis check entirely, NVMe drives comfortably clear any throughput\nbar this guide sets."],[575,"On the &#x2A;*\"General\"** tab:"],[582,"On the &#x2A;*\"Options\"** tab:"],[580,"On the &#x2A;*\"Services\"** tab:"],[111,"On the old node:"],[1033,"On the phone, make sure you have a Tor pathway. Zeus can\neither:"],[867,"On the remote host, list the target directory. You should see\nthe timestamped file plus `channel.backup.latest`:"],[737,"On your **regular computer** (not the Pi), run:"],[600,"On your regular computer, launch Raspberry Pi Imager."],[304,"Once `verificationprogress` clears `0.99999...`, trim the `dbcache`\nback to a sensible steady-state value so Electrs and LND have room\nto breathe, and turn transaction relay back on so the node earns\nits keep on the network."],[878,"Once all channels have settled, you can reopen new channels\nagainst the restored on-chain balance, you're back in\nbusiness."],[977,"Once the seed is recorded, exit the second session:"],[423,"Once you're connected, Sparrow is your window into the on-chain\nworld. A quick tour:"],[100,"Once you're synced, catching up after a restart takes minutes, not\ndays. Initial sync is a one-time cost."],[110,"Once you've copied the LND data directory off the old node, move it\naside so the old node can't start again by accident. A second LND\nnode broadcasting stale channel state means force-closed channels\nand, in the worst case, lost funds."],[13,"One-liner"],[965,"Open a **second** SSH session to the Pi. Become the `lnd` user\nand run `lncli create`:"],[765,"Open a fresh SSH session. You should land in a shell using your\nkey; password \\[A] should no longer be accepted."],[746,"Open a fresh terminal and connect again:"],[932,"Open a shell as the `lnd` user and set up the symlinks. LND\nlooks for its data in `~/.lnd` by default; pointing that at\n`/data/lnd` means every tool and tutorial that assumes the\ndefault path still works:"],[717,"Open a terminal on your regular computer:"],[804,"Open an SSH session to the Pi as the `admin` user:"],[1091,"Open Caddy's site config:"],[402,"Open sparrowwallet.com/download\nand grab:"],[371,"Open that address in the Tor Browser.\nNo certificates, no warnings, Tor's own end-to-end encryption\nreplaces TLS."],[361,"Open the Caddyfile:"],[1356,"Open the Caddyfile:"],[305,"Open the config:"],[1359,"Open the firewall and reload Caddy:"],[495,"Open the firewall for Electrum over TLS:"],[216,"Open the kernel command line:"],[681,"Open the Tor configuration:"],[1036,"Open Zeus, tap **Get Started**, then **Connect a node**."],[1193,"Open-source browser dashboard for managing and monitoring an LND node from any device."],[993,"Openoms maintains a\nlist of public altruistic watchtowers;\nadd two or three more for redundancy."],[261,"OpenTimestamps client (optional)"],[553,"Operating system"],[547,"Operating system, flash Raspberry Pi OS\nLite (64-bit) to the SSD and boot the Pi."],[524,"Optional guides for extra tooling, alternative software, and niche setups that complement t