s application and needs a recent LTS runtime. The\nNodeSource repository gives you upstream Node without waiting for\nDebian backports."],[1090,"RTL listens on `127.0.0.1:3000`, plain HTTP, bound to loopback.\nYou'll front it with **Caddy** (already installed in the Bitcoin\nsection) so you can reach it over HTTPS from anywhere on your LAN.\nCaddy's internal CA issues a self-signed cert on the fly, which\nyour browser will warn about exactly once when you trust the root."],[1079,"RTL ships a sample config; you copy it, edit a handful of fields,\nand you're done."],[1071,"RTL should not run as the `lnd` user, it's a web app with an\nexposed HTTP port, and a compromise there should not hand an\nattacker LND's admin macaroon. A dedicated `rtl` user keeps the\nblast radius small."],[810,"Run `sudo apt update && sudo apt full-upgrade` every few months to\npick up security fixes. Set a reminder if you're the forgetful type."],[145,"run as superuser"],[313,"Run BTC RPC Explorer on Node.js 22 behind Caddy HTTPS. Private lookup for blocks, transactions, mempool, fee estimates, UTXO queries. No leakage to public explorers."],[1347,"Run in the same `tmux` or `screen` session. A dropped SSH connection\nwould abort the build."],[332,"Run it as a systemd service."],[320,"Run it once by hand"],[282,"Run it with the username `raspibolt` and your &#x2A;*password \\[B]**\nfrom Preparations.\nPut a leading space in front of the command so bash keeps it out\nof your shell history, passwords don't belong in `~/.bash_history`:"],[1189,"Run lncli from a separate computer on your network to control your RaspiBolt Lightning node remotely."],[1155,"Run lncli from another computer on your network."],[1236,"Run RaspiBolt on an Odroid XU4 or compatible board."],[1315,"Run the full stack on testnet for safe experimentation."],[1240,"Run the RaspiBolt stack on an Odroid XU4 or compatible board as an alternative to a Raspberry Pi."],[958,"Running `lnd` by hand once is fine for the initial wallet setup.\nFor actual operation you want it under systemd so it starts at\nboot, restarts after crashes, and only comes up after `bitcoind`\nis ready."],[670,"Running a node at home makes you a first-class peer on the Bitcoin\nand Lightning networks. That's the good news. The flip side is that\nwithout privacy work, it also broadcasts to the world that somebody\nat **your** IP address runs a Lightning node, and services like\niplocation.net happily turn that IP\ninto a rough physical location."],[1386,"Running a testnet RaspiBolt lets you explore Bitcoin and Lightning\nwith play-money coins. The guide highlights every configuration\ndifference from the mainnet setup so you can build or test tools and\nintegrations without the risk of losing real sats."],[74,"Running your own Lightning node means you're not just a spectator,\nyou're part of the network that makes instant, low-fee Bitcoin\npayments possible."],[1371,"Safu Ninja"],[1374,"Safu Ninja is a DIY method for building\nfire- and water-resistant steel backups of your mnemonic seed\nphrases. It uses only off-the-shelf components, which means no\nthird-party vendor ever learns you own a hardware wallet or what\nthe device is guarding."],[239,"Same approach: stop the service, run in the foreground, read the\nstartup output carefully."],[703,"Same SSH key, same hardened `sshd` config, now reachable from\nanywhere without opening a port."],[1275,"Samourai Dojo"],[1278,"Samourai Dojo is the\nbacking server for Samourai Wallet. It exposes HD account and BIP47\nbalance and transaction data, serves unspent output lists, and\nbroadcasts transactions through your own `bitcoind`, removing the\nreliance on Samourai's hosted servers."],[762,"Sanity-check the config before restarting the daemon, this\ncatches typos that would otherwise lock you out:"],[795,"Save and exit. The radios stay off from the next reboot onward."],[501,"Save that `abcdefg...xyz.onion` in your password manager alongside\nthe one you may already have for SS