or common node-management commands."],[98,"Short answers to the questions that come up most often. If yours\nisn't here, the Telegram group and the\nGitHub issues are\nthe two places to ask."],[628,"Short USB 3 cable rated for SSDs (often included with the enclosure)"],[1161,"Simple shell script that prints a quick balance overview for your Lightning node."],[1169,"Simple shell script that prints a summary of all channels on your Lightning node."],[35,"Size"],[276,"Skim the output for multiple lines like:"],[44,"small, but irreplaceable"],[889,"So Bitcoin is running. Why bolt a second network on top of it?"],[598,"Some older Pi 4 boards shipped with a bootloader that can't boot\nfrom USB. You fix this once, using a microSD card, and then the Pi\nwill happily boot from USB forever after."],[489,"Sparrow and other wallets connect to Electrum servers over TLS on\nport 50002. Electrs itself serves plaintext on 50001, which is\nfine *inside* the Pi, but you want the network traffic encrypted\neven on your home LAN. `stunnel` is a tiny, purpose-built proxy that\nwraps a plain TCP socket in TLS and has been doing exactly that for\ntwo decades."],[444,"Sparrow checks for updates on launch and tells you when a new\nversion is out. Download from the releases page,\nverify the signature the same way you did at install, and replace\nthe installed version. The wallet files live in your user profile\nand survive any reinstall."],[400,"Sparrow is happiest when it's watch-only plus a hardware wallet on\na USB port. This is why, if you can swing it, you'll want a\nBitBox02, Coldcard, Jade, Ledger, or Trezor before you load real\nfunds into this setup."],[434,"Sparrow occasionally reaches outside your wallet: exchange rate\nfeeds, CoinJoin coordinators, block broadcasts through public APIs.\nBy default those go over clearnet and leak your laptop's public IP\nto whoever runs the other end."],[401,"Sparrow ships signed releases for Windows, macOS, and Linux. Verify\nbefore you run."],[1375,"Sparrow Terminal"],[1378,"Sparrow Terminal is a stripped-down build of Sparrow Wallet\nthat runs on systems without a graphical display. It's primarily a\nconfiguration utility for running Sparrow as a server daemon on your\nnode, with the GUI client connecting from another machine on your\nnetwork."],[409,"Sparrow's first-run wizard walks you straight into server\nconfiguration. If you're past that screen, you can reach the same\ndialog at any time with **Preferences → Server** (`Ctrl`-`P` on\nWindows/Linux, `Cmd`-`,` on macOS)."],[1379,"Specter Desktop"],[1382,"Specter Desktop wraps Bitcoin Core with\na convenient GUI and is purpose-built around multisignature setups\nusing hardware wallets and airgapped devices. It's a strong choice\nwhen you want self-custody of larger amounts with a second-factor\nsigning device."],[665,"SSH from anywhere with Tailscale"],[750,"SSH hardening with ed25519 keys, UFW firewall rules, fail2ban brute-force protection on systemd, open-files limit, disable Bluetooth and Wi-Fi radios."],[724,"SSH is built into every current macOS, Linux, and Windows, no extra\nclient to install. Connect with:"],[185,"SSH locked out, hdparm too slow, UAS quirks, fail2ban unban, ufw rules, bitcoind won't start, stuck IBD, LND chain sync. Fix the frikkin' little thing."],[189,"SSH lockout: login via console"],[707,"SSH to the Pi from macOS, Linux, or Windows OpenSSH. Command-line basics for first-timers. Generate and install an ed25519 key for passwordless login."],[55,"Start at the top and walk down:"],[873,"Start LND in the foreground as the `lnd` user:"],[920,"Start LND under systemd"],[1366,"Start the service and confirm it's running:"],[1001,"Start the service: `sudo systemctl start lnd` and tail the log\nuntil you see `synced_to_chain: true`."],[46,"Static channel backup"],[943,"Step back out of the `lnd` shell first, installing binaries into\n`/usr/local/bin` needs `admin`'s `sudo`:"],[963,"Still as `admin`, start LND in the foreground:"],[285,"Still as the `bitcoin` user, open the config:"],[935,"Still as the `lnd` user, grab the release archive, the manifest,\nand the maintainer's signature:"],[783,"Stock Debian `fail2ban` assumes `rsyslog` is writing `/var/log/auth.log`.\nOn Trixie it isn't, skip the two changes above and `fail2ban` will\nrun happily, read an empty log, and ban precisely nobody."],[354,"Stop it with `Ctrl`-`C` and exit back to `admin`:"],[232,"Stop the service and start it manually:"],[372,"Stop the service and switch to the app user:"],[998,"Stop the service: `sudo systemctl stop lnd`."],[623,"Storage"],[651,"Store the list in an open-source password manager like\nKeePassXC, free, offline, no cloud\ninvolved. When the build is done, keep any paper notes out of\nsight."],[829,"Strategy"],[1008,"Stream isolation caveat"],[30,"stunnel"],[490,"stunnel doesn't do automatic CA issuance the way Caddy does for HTTP.\nYou generate a self-signed certificate once and point the config at\nit. This takes a single command:"],[1078,"Success looks like `added NNN packages ... found 0 vulnerabilities`."],[802,"Swap"],[820,"Swap is the safety net: when RAM fills up, the system offloads idle\npages to \"swap\" instead of crashing. Compressed swap held in RAM\nsounds like a contradiction, but that's exactly what zram is, and\nit works beautifully for a node. On Raspberry Pi OS Trixie this is\nhandled out of the box by the &#x2A;*`rpi-swap`** service, which uses\n**zram** rather than a file on the SSD. Clever, and already running."],[480,"Switch to the `electrs` user and open a fresh config:"],[1363,"Switch to the `mempool` user and update the source:"],[340,"Switch to the new user and fetch the latest release tag:"],[148,"switch user"],[796,"System configuration"],[549,"System configuration, update\npackages, verify SSD speed, create the data directory, check swap."],[1243,"System overview"],[530,"System overviews, aliases, UPS integration, alternative hardware, and hardware-wallet SSH."],[799,"System update"],[832,"systemd path + service"],[918,"systemd unit"],[1060,"systemd unit"],[258,"Systemd unit"],[321,"Systemd unit"],[452,"Systemd unit"],[238,"Tail the debug log if you want to keep watching:"],[26,"Tailscale"],[704,"Tailscale makes remote SSH so frictionless that the old \"open\nport 22 to the internet\" pattern stops being necessary. Keep your\nufw rule scoped to the LAN (`192.168.0.0/24` or similar), the\ntailnet interface bypasses ufw by default on a fresh install, so\nTailscale devices can still reach the Pi without the firewall\nbeing in the way."],[690,"Tailscale sidesteps the whole mess. It\nbuilds a small, private mesh VPN between **your** devices using\nWireGuard. The Pi gets a stable private address (`100.x.y.z`) that\nonly devices you've authorised can reach. Your router does nothing.\nYour ISP sees encrypted traffic to a few discovery servers. Anyone\non the public internet sees nothing."],[691,"Tailscale's control plane is a proprietary SaaS. The data path is\nstill direct device-to-device WireGuard, Tailscale never sees your\ntraffic, but device authorisation runs through their servers. If\nthat doesn't fit your threat model,\nHeadscale is a fully open\nsource, self-hosted control plane that speaks the same protocol.\nThe Pi-side setup below works unchanged; you just point\n`tailscale up` at your Headscale server with `--login-server`.\nRunning Headscale itself is its own project, beyond this guide."],[1039,"Tap **Save node config**. First connection takes a while,\nZeus has to build a Tor circuit to your hidden service, so\ngive it a minute."],[1037,"Tap the &#x2A;*+** at the top right, give the node a nickname\n(`RaspiBolt` works), choose **LND** as the interface and\n**REST** as the connection type, then tap **Scan lndconnect\nconfig**."],[674,"Tell apt about the new repository. Modern Debian prefers the\n**deb822** format, looks unfamiliar compared to the old one-line\n`sources.list` syntax, but it's just one file, one stanza,\nclearly signed:"],[491,"Ten-year validity is fine for a LAN certificate. Wallets will warn\nonce that the certificate isn't from a public CA, you accept it,\nand they remember it from then on."],[833,"Test it"],[433,"Test. Sparrow's bundled Tor client handles the routing, you\ndon't need to run Tor on the laptop separately, as long as the\nURL ends in `.onion`."],[443,"Test. The secondary icon at bottom-right now reads \"External\nTor proxy enabled\"."],[77,"Thanks to every contributor who has filed an issue, opened a pull\nrequest, tested a fix on their own Pi, or helped a newcomer in the\nTelegram group. Thanks to everyone who\ncares about Bitcoin enough to run their own node, and to understand\nwhat it's actually doing."],[71,"That kind of independence shouldn't be reserved for people with a\nrack in a datacentre. A Raspberry Pi in the corner of your office,\nquietly validating every block that's ever been mined, is a\ndelightfully democratic piece of infrastructure."],[540,"The **Tor** daemon active, with its control port ready for\nBitcoin Core and Lightning to route their peer traffic privately."],[768,"The **Uncomplicated Firewall** (`ufw`) is Debian's friendly front-end\nto `iptables`. For now it only needs to allow SSH, every service\nyou add later will open its own port when the time comes."],[310,"The `--break-system-packages` flag is Debian 13's way of telling you\nthat it prefers packaged installs, in this case, upstream pip is\nthe only current source for the client, and it's an isolated tool\nthat does not touch the system Python."],[1358,"The `/api/*` block proxies API calls to the backend. Everything\nelse is served as a static file, falling back to `index.html` so\nAngular's client-side routing works for deep links."],[479,"The `bitcoin` group membership is what lets Electrs read\n`/data/bitcoin/.cookie` for RPC auth."],[339,"The `bitcoin` group membership is what lets the explorer read\n`/data/bitcoin/.cookie` for RPC authentication."],[405,"the `sparrow-<version>-manifest.txt.asc` signature."],[404,"the `sparrow-<version>-manifest.txt`,"],[836,"The 24-word seed restores your on-chain wallet. It does **not**\nrestore your Lightning channels. For that you need the **Static\nChannel Backup**, a small file LND updates every time a channel\nstate changes, and the missing half of a complete recovery plan."],[1274,"The BitBoxApp is the beginner-friendly\ncompanion app to the BitBox02 hardware wallet from Shift Crypto. By\nconfiguring it to connect directly to your RaspiBolt instead of\nShift's servers, you verify your own transactions and avoid leaking\nwallet addresses to a third party."],[632,"The Bitcoin blockchain is a big, growing thing. As of 2026 it's\naround **700 GB**, adding roughly 7 GB every month. On top of that,\nthe Electrs index (which makes your wallet fast) needs another\n\\~70 GB, and the operating system eats \\~20 GB for itself and logs. A\n1 TB drive is basically full on day one. Give yourself the 2 TB of\nbreathing room."],[1390,"The Bitcoin white paper was embedded in the blockchain in April 2013\ninside block 230,009. This guide walks through extracting and\nreassembling the PDF from your own verified blockchain data, a nice\ndemonstration that the foundational document of Bitcoin is, quite\nliterally, part of Bitcoin itself."],[1254,"The blockchain keeps growing, so the 1 TB drive that felt generous\nthree years ago will eventually fill up. This guide walks through\ncloning your node's data onto a larger drive and swapping it in\nwithout losing channels or state, minimizing downtime for your\nLightning node along the way."],[527,"The bonus pages are still being rewritten for v4. Each page links to\nthe v3 source while we work through the backlog."],[1137,"The bonus pages are still being rewritten for v4. Each page links to\nthe v3 source while we work through the backlog."],[1228,"The bonus pages are still being rewritten for v4. Each page links to\nthe v3 source while we work through the backlog."],[1299,"The bonus pages are still being rewritten for v4. Each page links to\nthe v3 source while we work through the backlog."],[526,"The bonus section collects everything that isn't part of the core\nBitcoin and Lightning node setup, alternative wallets, additional\ndashboards, privacy add-ons, quality-of-life tweaks, and experiments.\nThese guides are optional: the main path works without any of them."],[1348,"The built frontend lands in `~/mempool/frontend/dist/mempool/browser`."],[938,"The checksum proves the download wasn't corrupted in transit. It\ndoes not prove the manifest itself is authentic, for that you need\nto verify the PGP signature against the maintainer's public key.\nLND releases are signed by Olaoluwa \"Roasbeef\" Osuntokun."],[181,"The cleanest answer is to set it in your router, assign a DHCP\nreservation for the Pi's MAC address so it always lands on the same\nIP. Every consumer router can do this; the menu is usually called\n\"DHCP reservations\" or \"static leases\"."],[840,"The consequences matter:"],[343,"The explorer reads its config from `.env` in the install directory.\nA heavily commented template ships with the source. You only need to\nchange a handful of lines."],[353,"The explorer should bind to `http://127.0.0.1:3002`. If the console\nfills with RPC errors, Bitcoin Core is either not running or still\nreindexing, leave this alone until `bitcoin-cli getblockchaininfo`\nreports a `verificationprogress` at 1.0."],[359,"The explorer's Express server speaks HTTP on port 3002. You want\nbrowser access over HTTPS, and you want it without fighting\ncertificate tooling. **Caddy** handles this in five lines of config\nand issues itself a certificate from its own internal CA."],[474,"The fingerprint `SHA256:GifMn7F2swVKyn6MewbQHrYCs4i/bPK7gnwxhuPz/YA`\nis what matters; compare it against what you see in your terminal\nand against the key published in Roman's\nkeys repo."],[221,"The firewall should allow at least SSH (22), Bitcoin P2P (8333),\nand Lightning P2P (9735). If you're exposing Electrum or LND gRPC\nto your LAN, those too."],[488,"The first index pass walks the entire chain and builds the address\nindex on disk. On a Pi 5 with an SSD plan on **eight to twelve\nhours**; on a Pi 4, closer to a day. Don't try to connect Sparrow\nuntil the log quiets down and Electrs reports a caught-up tip,\npointing a wallet at an Electrum server that's still indexing will\njust time out."],[726,"The first time you connect, SSH asks you to confirm the Pi's host key\nfingerprint. Type `yes` and press Enter. You're now inside the Pi."],[15,"The full node. Verifies every block, maintains the UTXO set, speaks the peer-to-peer protocol."],[65,"The good old days"],[116,"The guide targets the Pi 5. The Pi 4 with 8 GB RAM works but\ninitial sync and Electrs indexing are noticeably slower. Any 64-bit\nARM or x86 board running Debian 13 \"Trixie\" should be compatible,\nbut is untested. The hard requirements are 8 GB RAM and a fast SSD."],[586,"The Imager writes the operating system and verifies every byte. When\nit reports &#x2A;*\"Success\"**, safely eject the SSD."],[517,"The install commands themselves take an afternoon. The blockchain\nsync is the long pole: on a Pi 5 with a decent SSD, the initial block\ndownload runs about two to five days, and Electrs then spends another\nhalf day to a day indexing on top of that. Neither step needs\nbabysitting, kick it off, glance at the log once a day, and come\nback when it's done."],[403,"the installer for your OS,"],[1089,"The log should end with\n`Server is up and running, please open the UI at http://localhost:3000`.\nExit the tail with `Ctrl-C`."],[298,"The mode should be `-rw-r-----` with owner `bitcoin` and group\n`bitcoin`."],[790,"The new limits kick in at the next login."],[289,"The node needs to start on boot and stay running, that's what\nsystemd is for. This unit runs `bitcoind` as the `bitcoin` user,\nlocks it into a few standard hardening primitives, and restarts on\nfailure with a sensible backoff."],[360,"The official Caddy apt repo is the right source. One-time setup:"],[567,"The official Raspberry Pi Imager\nhandles the whole \"write OS to SSD\" dance with a friendly interface.\nThis guide was written against **v1.9.4**; any recent version works."],[1053,"The onion address goes dark. Zeus immediately loses its connection."],[1046,"The onion hostname in the QR doesn't match\n`/var/lib/tor/hidden_service_lnd_rest/hostname`, regenerate the\nQR."],[76,"The original goal of the RaspiBolt guide, back in 2017, was simply\nbuying a Blockaccino. I used the\nEclair Lightning implementation\non testnet, because mainnet wasn't running yet. Oh, how time flies."],[636,"The Pi 4 still gets you there, just slower, initial block download\nand Electrs indexing take noticeably longer. Use the **4 GB model\nor larger** (8 GB preferred) and the **official 15W USB-C** power\nsupply. Wherever the Pi 4 needs a different step, this guide\nflags it."],[635,"The Pi 5 also supports NVMe SSDs through the official &#x2A;*M.2 HAT+**.\nNVMe builds index faster and syncs the blockchain noticeably\nquicker, at the cost of more hardware and a little more assembly.\nA good USB 3 SATA SSD is perfectly fine for everything in this\nguide, NVMe is a nice-to-have, not a requirement."],[590,"The Pi boots straight from the SSD. No microSD card needed."],[389,"The pick: **Sparrow Wallet** by Craig\nRaw. Active development, transparent about what it's doing under the\nhood, first-class support for every common hardware wallet, excellent\ncoin control, PSBTs, and batching. Sparrow is the right default for\nmost people using a RaspiBolt."],[974,"The RaspiBolt backup card\nis a nice printable template if you want one."],[1246,"The raspibolt-pulse\nscript prints a dense, color-coded status overview on every SSH\nlogin, block height, channel balances, disk usage, memory, and\nservice health all in one glance. It's the fastest way to confirm\nthe node is healthy before you start tinkering."],[849,"The rest of this page assumes the remote host is at\n`backup@10.0.0.50` with the SCB going into\n`/home/backup/raspibolt-scb/`. Substitute your own host, user,\nand path."],[395,"The rest of this page walks through Sparrow. The other wallets\nfollow roughly the same pattern, pick the \"Private Electrum\nServer\" option and point it at your Pi."],[283,"The script prints a line starting with `rpcauth=raspibolt:...$...`.\nCopy it, you'll paste it into the config file next."],[48,"The SD card or eMMC holds the OS and application configs only. No\nBitcoin data lives there."],[229,"The service user also needs write permission in the target\ndirectory. Verify by touching a file as that user:"],[1349,"The standard build script compiles all 33 translation locales, which\ntakes several hours on a Pi. The commands above build only the English\nsource locale and produce the same result."],[838,"The Static Channel Backup (SCB) is a single file:\n`/data/lnd/data/chain/bitcoin/mainnet/channel.backup`. LND rewrites\nit every time a channel opens, closes, or changes state. It\ncontains enough information, each peer's pubkey, the channel\nfunding outpoint, the commit transaction, for a **new** LND\ninstance to know who to ask for funds back."],[880,"The sync above is designed to keep the SCB fresh to within\nseconds. If you ever see a gap of days between the last sync and\n\"now\", something broke, and you need to know about it. A small\ncron job on the remote host that alerts on stale files is a good\nidea."],[850,"The sync has to run as the `lnd` user, that's the only account\nthat can read `channel.backup`. So the SSH key lives in\n`/home/lnd/.ssh/`."],[106,"The things worth keeping from an older node:"],[930,"The third command puts `admin` into the `lnd` group so you can\nrun `lncli` later without `sudo`."],[78,"The top 20 contributors on GitHub, by commit count:"],[933,"The two symlinks should show in cyan, not red. Red means a\nbroken link, usually because the target directory doesn't exist\nyet."],[226,"The whole point of running from an SSD is that application data\nlives on `/data`, not on the root filesystem. Each service user\nhas a symlink from `~/.<service>` to its data directory."],[669,"Then add **Tailscale**, a mesh VPN, so you can SSH into the Pi\nfrom anywhere without opening a single port on your router."],[971,"These 24 words are the only rope back to the on-chain funds on\nthis node. If the Pi dies, the SSD dies, or the house burns down,\nthe seed, and **only** the seed, can restore your wallet on a\nfresh LND."],[198,"Things break. Usually it's something small, a typo in a config\nfile, a permission that got flipped, a drive enclosure doing\nsomething funky. This page walks the common layers of a RaspiBolt\nsetup so you can find the break systematically rather than\nguess-and-check your way through it."],[1111,"This bonus page hasn't been rewritten for RaspiBolt v4 yet. The v3\nversion still works, see the original guide on GitHub\nwhile we port it over."],[1115,"This bonus page hasn't been rewritten for RaspiBolt v4 yet. The v3\nversion still works, see the original guide on GitHub\nwhile we port it over."],[1119,"This bonus page hasn't been rewritten for RaspiBolt v4 yet. The v3\nversion still works, see the original guide on GitHub\nwhile we port it over."],[1123,"This bonus page hasn't been rewritten for RaspiBolt v4 yet. The v3\nversion still works, see the original guide on GitHub\nwhile we port it over."],[1127,"This bonus page hasn't been rewritten for RaspiBolt v4 yet. The v3\nversion still works, see the original guide on GitHub\nwhile we port it over."],[1131,"This bonus page hasn't been rewritten for RaspiBolt v4 yet. The v3\nversion still works, see the original guide on GitHub\nwhile we port it over."],[1158,"This bonus page hasn't been rewritten for RaspiBolt v4 yet. The v3\nversion still works, see the original guide on GitHub\nwhile we port it over."],[1162,"This bonus page h